    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/syntax-tree-construction-parsing/003",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The MassQL language enables searching for patterns in MS1 data (for example, isotopic patterns and adduct mass shift) and MS/MS fragmentation spectra (for example, presence/absence of fragments and neutral losses), as well as applying chromatographic and ion mobility constraints. In addition, MassQL provides language support for user-defined tolerances, such as ion intensity and mass accuracy... each of these query elements can be combined with Boolean operators (for example, AND, OR and NOT) to form more complex queries.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper describes domain-specific operators (m/z, intensity, fragmentation patterns) and Boolean logic, matching the card's scope description.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1038-s41592-025-02660-z",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "syntax-tree-construction-parsing",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Specifically, use it when the query syntax combines SQL-inspired constructs with domain-specific operators (e.g., m/z ranges, intensity thresholds, fragmentation patterns in mass spectrometry) that require both syntactic parsing and semantic constraint enforcement.",
